<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Amelanchier</i> <i>utahensis</i>, <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>intricatus</i>, <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>montanus</i> or <i>Philadelphus</i> <i>microphyllus</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Amelanchier</i> <i>alnifolia</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>patula</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>nova</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Chrysothamnus</i> <i>viscidiflorus</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>viridis</i>, <i>Glossopetalon</i> <i>spinescens</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>virginiana</i> and/or <i>Purshia</i> <i>tridentata</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Juniperus</i> <i>occidentalis</i>, <i>Juniperus</i> <i>osteosperma</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>longaeva</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is sparse to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Cercocarpus intricatus</i> > 55% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Amelanchier utahensis</i> or <i>Cercocarpus montanus</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Cercocarpus intricatus</i> or <i>Philadelphus microphyllus</i> is > 30% relative cover in the shrub layer (Reyes et al. 2020a).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Xeric mountain ridges, rocky outcrops, and steep upper slopes. Soils are skeletal and often calcareous or volcanic.  </div>
</div>

        
