<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Amelanchier utahensis </i>is a multi-branched, deciduous shrub from 2 to 4 m in height. Its fruits are purplish berry-like pomes. It can be a prolific seeder especially in years of good moisture. Historically, it was considered a variety of <i>A. alnifolia </i> (Zlatnik 1999e). Similar to other taxa of this alliance, it grows on open rocky slopes and frequently occurs in the understory of many other alliances.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Cercocarpus intricatus </i>is a long-lived, intricately branched, tall shrub that grows up to 3 m in height. It is characteristic of nutrient- and water-deficient, mountainous desert environments in the Great Basin. Little is known about its reproductive biology, though it is likely similar to <i>C. ledifolius</i>. It mainly reproduces by seed and is a sporadic producer (Kitchen 2002).  Some references consider this taxon to be a variety of <i>C. ledifolius</i> (Jepson Flora Project, 2019).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Cercocarpus intricatus </i>has a narrow distribution in California. It locally dominates, often as the sole shrub, on calcareous rock outcrops with soil in the northern Mojave Desert and southeastern Great Basin. The environment is usually significantly warmer and drier than that of <i>C. ledifolius </i>stands. <i>C. intricatus </i>usually occurs in the low sagebrush belt, the <i>Pinus monophylla </i>belt, and rarely near or at timberline. Hybrid plants of these two <i>Cercocarpus </i> species occur between 2750 and 3050 m in a zone between the <i>P. monophylla </i>woodlands and subalpine forests of <i>P. flexilis </i>and <i>P. longaeva </i>(Brayton and Mooney 1966).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Cercocarpus montanus </i>is a long-lived shrub or small tree that grows up to 8 m in height. In fruit, the styles expand with silvery, plumose hairs and seeds are wind dispersed. Most California references use the names <i>C. betuloides </i>and <i>C. minutiflorus </i>for this species and its varieties.  Stands outside the Modoc Plateau region are ascribed to the <i>Cercocarpus montanus </i>Alliance.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Philadelphus microphyllus </i>is an erect, multi-stemmed deciduous shrub that can grow from 0.9 to 3 m in height. It is found on rocky slopes, cliffs, and within pinyon/juniper woodlands. Its seeds are gravity and wind dispersed. Morphological variability in <i>Philadelphus microphyllus </i>has resulted in past complexities with synonymy (Bonner and Karrfalt 2008). Currently only <i>Philadelphus microphyllus </i>is recognized by USDA PLANTS (2020) and the Jepson Flora Project (2019), though many subspecies and varieties have been described in the past. Like other associations within this alliance, stands of <i>Philadelphus microphyllus </i> are found along xeric, calcareous mountain ridges and rocky slopes, thus vegetation stands dominated by this species have been provisionally placed within this alliance. Further sampling of this type is necessary to resolve its placement. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been expanded from the <i>Cercocarpus intricatus </i>Alliance that was cited in the 2009 publication <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, Second Edition</i> to include stands of <i>Amelanchier utahensis </i>, <i>Philadelphus microphyllus, </i>and <i>Cercocarpus montanus </i> that occur on the Modoc Plateau and other areas of transmontane California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
