    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gj-k). Stands of <i>Amelanchier utahensis</i> have been sampled at the top of Hermit Butte (M261Gk) and stands of <i>Cercocarpus montanus </i>have been sampled in Silva Flat (M261Gj) (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aj). Sparse stands of <i>Cercocarpus intricatus</i> have been sampled in Mojave National Preserve at Clark Mountain (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). Stands of <i>Cercocarpus intricatus</i> and <i>Philadelphus microphyllus</i> occur at Wyman Canyon and Silver Canyon in the White Mountains (Brayton and Mooney 1966). Stands are found primarily on steep, rocky canyon walls and outcrops along creeks feeding into Deep Springs Valley (Reyes et al. 2020a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ei). One stand of <i>Amelanchier utahensis</i> has been sampled on a northeast facing slope at the northwest corner of Sierra Valley (Ratchford et al 2021b, in progress).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-d, Ff). Stands of <i>Cercocarpus intricatus</i> at Whippoorwill Flat RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1990d) in the Inyo Mountains are similar to those scattered on calcareous outcrops in the Cottonwood, Last Chance, Panamint, and other large ranges in the section (Thomas et al. 2004). Other stands of <i>Philadelphus microphyllus </i>occur sporadically in the section including near Cerro Gordo Mine on steep calcareous cliffs.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cercocarpus intricatus </i>provides cover for wild animals and forage for wild ungulates and domesticated animals in rugged and remote terrain. The species may possess nitrogen-fixing roots similar to its close relatives, though seedling and shrub growth rates are slow (Kitchen 2002).

<i>Amelanchier utahensis </i>provides forage for wildlife and ungulates, including domesticated animals. Its berries are preferred fruit for small mammals and birds, including sage grouse. It can be used for erosion control in revegetation projects, though establishment may be slow (Zlatnick 1999e).

Fires occurring at short intervals have the potential to cause significant changes in species composition and deplete seed banks. <i>Cercocarpus montanus </i>is valuable browse in much of the state, but excessive browsing kills branches (Uchytil 1991b). Stands on steep, rocky slopes are not as threatened by unnaturally high fire frequency as those in other sites with more fuel buildup.

<i>Philadelphus microphyllus </i>can resprout after fire and has been useful in revegetation efforts on steep, rocky slopes after disturbance (Monsen et al. 2004). This species is known to provide forage and cover for wildlife, including deer, and less commonly by livestock (Bonner and Karrfalt 2008, USDA Forest Service 1937). </div>
</div>

    

    

